I&#39;m not sure if I fully understand your question however having a static configuration class is a popular way of doing this. 

    public static class Config
    {
        public static String ConnectionString { get; set; }
    }

This is instead of using configuration manager elsewhere in the application. To access the properties anywhere you can just do `Config.ConnectionString`.

To actually populate the `Config` class, you can specify separate classes to populate them and run it in the start up. For standard .NET:

    public class ConfigSetup
    {
        public static void SetupConfig()
        {
            Config.ConnectionString = ConfigurationManager.AppSettings[&quot;ConnectionString&quot;];
        }
    }

For .NET core in Startup.cs:

    public IConfiguration _config { get; }
    
    public Startup(IHostingEnvironment env)
    {
        _environmentPath = env.ContentRootPath;
    
        _config = new ConfigurationBuilder().SetBasePath(env.ContentRootPath).AddJsonFile(&quot;appSettings.json&quot;).Build();
    }
    
    public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IHostingEnvironment env, ILoggerFactory loggerFactory)
    {
        Config.ConnectionString = _config[&quot;ConnectionString&quot;];
    }

So you may have several `ConfigSetup`s for each project type but only need to run the one which is relevant to the current project. This will mean you will keep the code the same everywhere apart from the startup.

